<subSubSection lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="283" pageId="22" pageNumber="279" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,2009,2035]" lastBlockId="26.[151,1437,153,323]" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="283" pageId="22" pageNumber="279">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,260,2009,2035]" pageId="22" pageNumber="279">Remarks</emphasis>
. See 
<bibRefCitation author="He, Z. - Q. &amp; Zhang, Y. &amp; Webb, M. D." box="[329,500,2009,2035]" pageId="22" pageNumber="279" pagination="25 - 30" refId="ref13690" refString="He, Z. - Q., Zhang, Y. &amp; Webb, M. D. (2008) An unusual new genus and species of Hecalini leafhopper from southern China) Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Deltocephalinae). Zootaxa, 1896 (1), 25 - 30. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1896.1.2" type="journal article" year="2008">
He 
<emphasis box="[373,433,2009,2035]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="279">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
for complete description. This genus is easily distinguished from other Chinese Hecalina by the absence of color bands on head and pronotum and the elongate overall shape with a long vertex. Additionally, the aedeagus lacks apical processes but has a recurved basal process, the male pygofer has an inner process (Fig. 221), the subgenital plates bear mesal processes ((Figs. 223–224), and the 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1141,1152,224,238]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="283">st</superScript>
valvula of the female has a long row of short vertical striations (Figs. 212, 213). As discussed in the Introduction, this genus is not closely related to other 
<taxonomicName box="[328,426,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="285" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hecalini">Hecalini</taxonomicName>
, but is retained in the tribe until a well-supported alternate tribal placement is determined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
